'''Cornelis de Heem''' (8 April 1631 (baptized) – 17 May 1695 (buried) <ref>[https://rkd.nl/en/explore/artists/36837]</ref>) was a [[still-life]] painter associated with both [[Flemish Baroque painting|Flemish Baroque]] and [[Dutch Golden Age painting]].<ref name="grove">Sam Segal, "Cornelis (Jansz.) de Heem," ''[[Grove Art Online]]'', [[Oxford University Press]] [accessed 21 April 2008].</ref> He was a member of a large family of still-life specialists,<ref>[http://www.getty.edu/vow/ULANFullDisplay?find=Cornelis+de+heem&role=&nation=&page=1&subjectid=500018142 Getty Union name Index] explicates the relationships (though clearly erroneous in one of the Jan Jansz. birth-dates)</ref> of which his father, [[Jan Davidszoon de Heem]] (1606–1684), was the most significant.<ref>Sam Segal, "Jan Davidsz. de Heem," ''[[Grove Art Online]]'', [[Oxford University Press]] [accessed 21 April 2008].</ref>
Cornelis was [[baptise]]d in [[Leiden]] on 8 April 1631,<ref name="grove" /> and moved with his family to Antwerp in 1636. He appears to have been trained by his father in Antwerp, who, like him, was born in the [[Dutch Republic]] but died in the [[Southern Netherlands]]. Jan's subsequent career, like many painters—especially after the [[Peace of Westphalia]] in 1648—moved fluidly between the two traditionally-connected areas of the north and south [[Low Countries]]. He became a member of the [[Antwerp painters' guild]] in 1660, and from 1667 until the late 1680s he was variously active in [[Utrecht (city)|Utrecht]], [[IJsselstein]], and [[The Hague]].<ref name="grove" /> It is often not easy to distinguish the works of the different members of the family, which included his brother [[Jan Janszoon de Heem|Jan Jansz.]], nephew Jan Jansz. II, and son [[David Corneliszoon de Heem|David Cornelisz.]] (1663–after? 1718), who all painted mostly flower and fruit pieces in a similar style and probably often collaborated.<ref>Neil MacLaren, ''The Dutch School, 1600-1800, Volume I'', National Gallery Catalogues'', p. 163-4, 1991, National Gallery, London, {{ISBN|0-947645-99-3}}</ref> Cornelis's works, however, tend to be small, display a preference for strong blues, and, over time, shifted away from the painterly style preferred by his father.<ref name="grove" /> He died in [[Antwerp]], aged 64. {{De Heem family}}
<gallery> Image:Cornelis de Heem 01.jpg Image:Cornelis de Heem 02.jpg Image:Cornelis de Heem 03.jpg Image:Cornelis de Heem 04.jpg File:1657 de Heem Prunkstilleben mit kopulierenden Spatzen anagoria.JPG|''Pageantry Still Life with copulating sparrows'', 1657, [[Städelsches Kunstinstitut]] </gallery>
