{{Infobox company| name = Navibulgar| type = [[public company|State owned]] | foundation = 1892 | location = [[Varna]], [[Bulgaria]]| num_employees = 4,000 (2006), revenue = [[Image:Green Arrow Up.svg|12px]] US$267&nbsp;million (2006) | industry = [[Shipping]] | }}
'''Navibulgar''' is a [[Bulgaria]]n [[shipping]] company, the largest in the country, with a fleet of 70 vessels: 46 [[Bulk cargo|bulk carriers]], 9 [[Intermodal container|container vessels]], 5 [[tanker (ship)|tanker and chemical vessels]], and 10 [[cargo|combined tonnage vessels]], including their new 30,700-tonne ship, which became a part of their fleet in June 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europost.bg/article?id=4797|title=NaviBulgar gets its new 30,700-tonne ship|publisher=Europost|accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref>
==Acquisitions== In 2002, the company acquired Varna shipyard for $16.1&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marinelink.com/news/article/navibulgar-finalizes-varna-shipyard-acquisition/321136.aspx|title=Navibulgar Finalizes Varna Shipyard Acquisition|publisher=Marine Link|accessdate=11 March 2013}}</ref>
In May 2014, Navibulgar completed its set of modern domestically built [[handymax]] ships with a deal for a Greek-owned [[bulker]]. The vessel is named ''Wanderlust''<ref>http://www.tradewindsnews.com/vessel/?id=F190543BECA49D04</ref> and was originally ordered for design and building in 1997.<ref>http://www.tradewindsnews.com/drycargo/337810/nmb-buys-primal-bulker</ref>
