{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = The Emperor: Downfall of an Autocrat | title_orig = Cesarz | translator = [[William R. Brand]] and [[Katarzyna Mroczkowska-Brand]] | image = The Emperor (book).jpg | author = [[Ryszard Kapuściński]] | cover_artist = | country = Poland | language = [[Polish language|Polish]] | series = | genre = [[Non-fiction]]/[[Literature]] | publisher = [[Vintage International]] | release_date = 1978 | media_type = Print (Paperback) | pages = 164 | isbn = 0-679-72203-3 | oclc= 19822583 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The Emperor: Downfall of an Autocrat''''', published in 1978, is [[Poles|Polish]] [[journalist]] [[Ryszard Kapuściński]]'s analysis of the decline and fall of [[Haile Selassie|Haile Selassie's]] regime in [[Ethiopia]]. In 1974, while the [[Derg|Ethiopian Army]] was still busy consolidating power, Kapuściński "traveled to Ethiopia to seek out and interview Selassie's servants and closest associates on how the Emperor had ruled and why he fell."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.powells.com/biblio?isbn=0679722033 |title=The Emperor by Ryszard Kapuscinski - Powell's Books |publisher=Powells.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-03}}</ref> In large part, the book is a study of the workings of a [[royal court]]. It is said that this book is intended to be allegorical of the government of Poland, especially [[Edward Gierek]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/05/29/books/the-dictator-s-downfall.html |title=The Dictator'S Downfall |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=1983-05-29 |accessdate=2013-10-03}}</ref>
==Contents==
===The Throne=== Section one focuses on the constitution of Emperor Haile Selassie's imperial court.
===It's Coming, It's Coming=== Section two focuses on the [[1960 Ethiopian coup attempt|attempted coup]] led by [[Mengistu Neway]] on December 13, 1960, and its repercussions.
===The Collapse=== This section focuses on the ultimate downfall of Selassie, featuring an account by his valet, who was the last remaining servant in the Emperor's court. This is followed by two short newspaper articles on the Emperor's last few years of life, which show that he still believed himself to be the true leader of Ethiopia.
==Theatre== "The Emperor" had a world premiere in [[London]]'s [[Young Vic]] on 3 September 2016.<ref>http://www.youngvic.org/whats-on/the-emperor</ref> The play was well received by the reviewers.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2016/sep/09/the-emperor-review-kathryn-hunter-young-vic-haile-selassie |title=The Emperor review – majestic Kathryn Hunter gives 10 great performances |publisher=theguardian.com |date=2016-09-09 |accessdate=2016-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.ft.com/content/11ff3cf6-7680-11e6-bf48-b372cdb1043a |title=The Emperor, Young Vic, London — ‘Riveting’ |publisher=ft.com |date=2016-09-11 |accessdate=2016-10-15}}</ref>
